<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,311,1271,1296]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Genitalia</emphasis>
<materialsCitation location="Uncus" municipality="Phallus straight" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" specimenCount="1" specimenCount-male="1">
<specimenCount box="[320,339,1271,1290]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
(
<figureCitation box="[354,442,1272,1296]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–82" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1928,1951]" captionTargetBox="[190,1400,188,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-71@72.[182,1406,169,1897]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 78–82. Male genitalia of Mesophleps spp. 78. M. parvella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30915; 79. M. aspina sp. nov. holotype, slide no. 30960; 80. M. truncatella sp. nov. holotype, slide no. 30889; 81. M. undulatella sp. nov. holotype, slide no. 30966; 82. M. geodes (Meyrick), slide no. 30939." pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Figs 82</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[455,486,1272,1296]" captionStart="FIGURES 83–88" captionStartId="73.[151,264,1951,1974]" captionTargetBox="[204,1386,194,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-71@73.[181,1405,181,1930]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURES 83–88. Male genitalia of Mesophleps spp., genus? and Sarotorna. 83. M. catericta (Meyrick), slide no. 30972; 84. M. tetrachroa (Lower), slide no. 30945; 85. M. tephrastis (Meyrick), slide no. 30948; 86. M. chloranthes (Lower), slide no. 30968; 87.? mesophracta (Turner), slide no. 30958; 88. Sarotorna mesoleuca (Lower), slide no. 11620, ANIC." pageId="47" pageNumber="48">83</figureCitation>
). 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:039B87F3A6414A12FF2FFC013759F93E:8EED603EA6414A12FE44FB2C3168FACA" box="[508,580,1273,1296]" municipality="Phallus straight" name="Uncus" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Uncus</location>
sub-rectangular or distally rounded and medially constricted; gnathos arms medially fused to single hook, valva simple. 
<collectingMunicipality box="[679,859,1308,1332]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Phallus straight</collectingMunicipality>
, with moderately swollen base, evenly tapered to sharp point or angled in middle with abruptly narrowed distal portion
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1050,1765]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,312,1380,1405]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Genitalia</emphasis>
º (
<figureCitation box="[356,514,1380,1404]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–111" captionStartId="77.[151,264,1926,1949]" captionTargetBox="[209,1358,192,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-75@77.[181,1405,177,1905]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 106–111. Female genitalia of Mesophleps spp. 106. M. nairobiensis Li &amp; Zheng, slide no. 30825; 107. M. coffeae sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30796; 108. M. truncatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30891; 109. M. undulatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30965; 110. M. geodes (Meyrick), slide no. 30937; 111. M. catericta (Meyrick), slide no. 30973." pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Figs 110, 111</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[528,632,1380,1404]" captionStart="FIGURES 131–142" captionStartId="80.[151,264,1833,1856]" captionTargetBox="[196,1376,213,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-127@80.[181,1405,193,1813]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="FIGURES 131–142. Female segment VIII of Mesophleps spp. 131. M. ochracella (Turati), slide no. 30982; 132. M. unguella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30956; 133. M. gigantella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 15836; 134. M. sp. (Yunnan), slide no. L95070; 135. M. albilinella (Park), slide no. L03077; 136. M. nairobiensis Li &amp; Zheng, slide no. 30825; 137. M. coffeae sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30796; 138. M. parvella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30951; 139. M. truncatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30891; 140. M. undulatella sp. nov. paratype, slide no. 30965; 141. M. geodes (Meyrick), slide no. 30937; 142. M. catericta (Meyrick), slide no. 30973." pageId="47" pageNumber="48">141, 142</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales sub-rectangular, width about three-times length, apophyses posteriores less than twice length of apophyses anteriores. Ostium bursae membranous; ductus bursae of moderate length; ductus seminalis from ductus or cervix bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1050,1765]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,315,1488,1512]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Despite several specializations such as the unusual genitalia we believe that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Li &amp; Sattler" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[1174,1250,1488,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geodes">
<emphasis box="[1174,1250,1488,1512]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">geodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is merely a specialized member of the same clade and consequently synonymize the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1929" box="[982,1209,1524,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Bucolarcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[982,1109,1524,1548]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Bucolarcha</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" box="[1271,1402,1524,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1271,1402,1524,1548]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Mesophleps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on account of the abdominal bands of microtrichia, and the larval biology (seed feeder in the pods of leguminous trees).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1050,1765]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
The two species placed in this group differ from each other in many characters but are tentatively placed together because they uniquely share the broad band of microtrichia on abdominal TVIII of the male (elsewhere in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" box="[151,285,1668,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Mesophleps" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,285,1668,1692]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Mesophleps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only on TIV–VII) and, in the female, the unusually broad papillae anales.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
